<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>This madman's folly, is not to be borne&mdash;if my lord too &s;hou'd di&s;cover him here, the con&s;equences might be dreadful, and the &s;cheme of Ennui's play all un$$$e&mdash;Sir, I de&s;ire you'll quit my hou&s;e immediately&mdash;Oh! I'll be reveng'd I'm determin'd.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's an exit&mdash;very well! I've got incident however&mdash;'&s;aith I've noble talents&mdash;to extract gold from le$$$ has been the t$$l of numberle&s;s philo&s;ophers: but I extract it from a better metal, human frailty&mdash;Oh it's a
<PB N="18" REF="18">great thing to be a dramatic genius! a very great thing indeed?</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>As he is going off Lord</HI> Scratch <HI>enters.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your mo&s;t obedient!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your mo&s;t devoted!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very warm Tragedy weather &s;ir&mdash;but for my part I hate &s;ummer, and I'll tell you why&mdash;the Theatres are then &s;hut up &s;ir, and when I pa&s;s by their doors in an evening it makes me melancholy&mdash;I look upon them as the tombs of departed friends that were wont to in|&s;truct and delight me&mdash;I don't know how you feel&mdash;per|haps you are not in my way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps you don't write for the &s;tage&mdash;if you do there is a capital character in the hou&s;e for a farce!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what is all this? who are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whom am I!&mdash;Here's a que&s;tion? In the&s;e times who can tell who he is? for ought I know, I may be great uncle to your&s;elf, or fir&s;t cou&s;in to Lady Waitfort&mdash; to the very woman I was about to&mdash;but no matter, &s;ince you're &s;o very inqui&s;itive, do you know who you are?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who am I&mdash;why I'm Lord Scratch!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Peer! contemptible! when I a&s;k a man who he is, do you think I want to know what are his titles and &s;uch &s;tuff&mdash;no, Old Scratch, I want to know what he has written, when he had the curtain up, and whether he's a true &s;on of the Drama&mdash;hark'ye, don't make your&s;elf unea&s;y on my account&mdash;in my next Pantomime perhaps I'll let you know who I am, Old Scratch!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;toni&s;hing! can this be Lady Waitfort's Hou&s;e?&mdash;"Very warm tragedy weather &s;ir, in my next pantomime let you know who I am,"&mdash;"gad I'll go and inve&s;tigate the matter immediately, and if &s;he has wrong'd me, by the blood of the Scratches, I'll bring the whole bu&s;ine&s;s before Parliament, make a &s;peech ten hours long, reduce the price of opium, and &s;et the nation in a tumult.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;Library at Lady <HI>WAITFORT'S.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> VAPID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Either this hou&s;e is a labyrinth, or I in reflecting on my incident have forgot my&s;elf; for &s;o it is, I can't find my way out&mdash;Eh! who have we here?&mdash;by the &s;ixtieth night, my little partner!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="19" REF="19">
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARIANNE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>The poet I danced with!&mdash;he little thinks how much I've thought of him &s;ince? Sir!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(curt&s;eying.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am,</P>
<STAGE><HI>(bowing.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope &s;ir, you caught no cold the other night.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, ma'am, I was much nearer a fever than a cold&mdash;pray ma'am what is your &s;tudy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been reading "<HI>All</HI> for <HI>Love</HI>"&mdash;pray &s;ir do you know any thing about plays?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know any thing about plays! there's a que&s;tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know &s;o much about them, that I once acted at a private Theatre.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you acted for your own amu&s;ement and nobody's el&s;e: what was the play?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't tell.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't tell.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;nobody knew&mdash;it's a way they have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then they act no play of mine&mdash;&s;o, then with all this partiality for the &s;tage&mdash;perhaps you wou'd be content with a dramati&s;t for life? particularly if his morals were fine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord! I don't care about fine morals, I'de ra|ther my hu&s;band had fine teeth&mdash;and I'm told mo&s;t wo|men of fa&s;hion are of the &s;ame opinion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure they are&mdash;but cou'd you really con|&s;ent to run away with a poet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Faith with all my heart&mdash;they never have any money you know, and as I have none, our di&s;tre&s;s wou'd be compleat, and if we had any luck our adventures wou'd become public, and then we &s;hou'd get into a Novel at la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Into a pri&s;on more porbably&mdash;if &s;he goes on in this way, I mu&s;t dramatize her fir&s;t, and run away with her afterwards <STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></STAGE> come are you ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT. <HI>(without.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Tell my lord I'll wait in the Library.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Lord! my aunt, what's to be done!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's to be done! why?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>She mu&s;tn't find you here&mdash;&s;he'll be the death of me &s;he's &s;o violent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'm not afraid of her&mdash;&s;he's no critic.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="20" REF="20">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but if you've any pity for me&mdash;here hide your&s;elf for a moment behind this &s;opha, and I'll get her out of the room directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Behind this &s;opha! here's a new &s;ituation!</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>gets behind the Sopha,</HI> Marianne <HI>&s;its on it, takes out her working bag, and &s;ings.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LADY WAITFORT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Toll de roll, &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marianne, how came you here? I de&s;ire you'll leave the room directly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave the room aunt?</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Looks towards the Sopha.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, leave the room immediately&mdash;what are you looking at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing aunt, nothing&mdash;Lord, lord! what will become of poor Mr Poet.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, here's my lord&mdash;now to mention En|nui's play, and if it does but prejudice him again&s;t him, Willoughby marries Loui&s;a, and Neville is in my own power.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD SCRATCH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>That cur&s;t pantomime ruffian&mdash;nobody knows any thing about him&mdash;perhaps my lady has got a &s;udden touch of the Dramatic Maniac, and prefers him&mdash; here &s;he is, now if &s;he &s;hou'd talk about the &s;tage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray be &s;eated my lord&mdash;I want to a&s;k you a favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;k me a &s;avour! is it po&s;&s;ible my lady?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, for our friend Ennui&mdash;what do you think he has done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>What!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Turn'd author&mdash;he has written a comedy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>A comedy! She has it!</P>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, 'tis very true, and it has been appro|ved of by men of the fir&s;t dramatic fame!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dramatic fame! She has it, damn me but &s;he has it.</P>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, if you need further proof my lord, it has been approv'd by the manager of one of the theatres, and the curtain is to be drawn up next winter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>The curtain drawn up! Look'ye ma'am, I care no more for the manager, or his theatre, or his
<PB N="21" REF="21">prompter&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Vapid <HI>rai&s;es his head from behind the Sopha, then pops it down.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now my lord, the favour I have to a&s;k of you is this. Promi&s;e me to peru&s;e the play, make alte|rations, and wri$e the Epilogue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Write the Epilogue! Fire and fore fa|thers!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, or the Prologue!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Prologue! Blood and gunpowder!</P>
<STAGE>(Vapid <HI>jumps up from behind the Sopha, and &s;macks Lord</HI> Scratch <HI>on the back.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prologue or Epilogue! I am the man&mdash;I'll write you both.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>There he is again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh I &s;hall faint with vexation, my lord I beg you'll mi&s;interpret nothing&mdash;every thing &s;hall be ex|plain'd to you. Marianne!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(calling).</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's the curtain up with a vengeance.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARIANNE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>An&s;wer me directly, how came that gentle|man in this apartment? I know it is &s;ome trick of yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>(coming down the &s;tage.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure never was a|ny thing &s;o fortunate! Upon my &s;oul I beg your pardon; but cur&s;e me if I can help laughing to think how lucky it was for you both I happened to be behind the &s;opha, ha. ha. ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR. <HI>(As if taking the hint.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Faith no more can I&mdash;To be &s;ure it was the luckie&s;t thing in the world ha, ha, ha.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>$ere they $oth laugh and point to Lord</HI> Scratch <HI>and La|dy</HI> Wait&s;ort, <HI>who look amaz'd.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I in&s;i&s;t you'll lay a&s;ide this levity, and in&s;tantly explain how you came into this hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;Ha, ha, ha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;ir&mdash;explain&mdash;and di&s;patch&mdash;I in|treat you di&s;patch&mdash;I have &s;o much to &s;ay&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear old lady&mdash;I'll take care of you,</P>
<STAGE><HI>(in a low tone of voice.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>None of your whi&s;pering&mdash;&s;peak out &s;ir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;then I came here, &s;ir, by her Lady&s;hip's own appointment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My own appointment! I &s;hall run wild!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="22" REF="22">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;you have hardly forgot your own hand writing&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>(feeling for the letter.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her own hand writing! Get on &s;ir&mdash;I be&s;eech you get on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why look'ye Old Scratch&mdash;you &s;eem to be an admirer of this lady's&mdash;now I think it my duty as a moral Dramati&s;t&mdash;mark me, &s;ir, a moral Dramati&s;t, to expo&s;e hypocri&s;y&mdash;therefore, &s;ir, there is the letter, read it and be convinced of your error.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well! Have you, done &s;ir? have you done? con&s;ider I am a Peer of the Realm, and &s;hall die if I don't talk.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now &s;ir, I mu&s;t beg a &s;avour of you, <STAGE><HI>(gets clo&s;e to him)</HI></STAGE>&mdash;keep the whole a &s;ecret, for if it gets hack|nied it lo&s;es all its force.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Granted! granted&mdash;I'll grant you any thing &s;o you will but get on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Between our&s;elves&mdash;I mean&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No pau&s;es &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>To bring it all on the &s;tage! hu&s;h! &s;ay nothing&mdash;it will have a capital effect, and brother Bards will wonder where I &s;tole it&mdash;Your &s;ituation will be wonder|ful&mdash;you havn't an idea how ridiculous you'll look&mdash;you'll laugh very much at your&s;elf I a&s;&s;ure you, your part &s;hall be done well! little Cherry &s;hall do you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is all this?&mdash;well&mdash;now I will &s;peak&mdash;I'll wait no longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, I'll take care of you&mdash;Fal&s;taff in the Buck ba&s;ket will be nothing to it&mdash;he was only the dupe of another man's wife, but you'll be the dupe of your own you know&mdash;"think of that Ma&s;ter Brook, think of that,"&mdash;well I'll write you the Prologue and Epilogue; but you need not &s;end me the Comedy, we never connect either with the play now&mdash;your friend may be damn'd you know and don't chu&s;e to &s;uffer for his &s;ins&mdash;I like to live and &s;ight another day&mdash;Marianne farewell my dear&mdash;Old Lady <HI>adieu</HI>&mdash;I'll do your bu&s;ine&s;s depend on't.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's gone without hearing me! then there's an end of every thing, for now here I &s;tand&mdash;once a Barri&s;ter&mdash;&s;ince a Country Gentleman, and now a Peer, and tho' I've made twenty attempts to &s;peak, I
<PB N="23" REF="23">can't be heard a &s;yllable&mdash;Mercy, mercy! What will the world come to! a Peer and not to be heard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, a&s;&s;ured of my own innocence, I have no doubt of ju&s;tifying my&s;elf, and even by means of that letter encrea&s;ing your affection&mdash;it was written to another per&s;on&mdash;your ungrateful nephew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>My nephew!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes &s;ir, I cou'd not perceive him lo&s;ing the e&s;teem of his friends without having the de&s;ire to reclaim him&mdash;indeed I knew no better mode of fulfilling my pro|ject, than by per&s;onally warning him of his &s;ituation&mdash;for this purpo&s;e I wrote that letter, and I never thought it would be thus mi&s;us'd&mdash;if there is any improper warmth in the expre&s;&s;ions it only proceeds from my anxiety of en&s;uring an interview&mdash;I hope &s;ir, you are &s;atisfied?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I believe you my lady, and I &s;hou'd be perfectly &s;atisfied if I cou'd forget your pa&s;&s;ion for the &s;tage, and that madman behind the &s;opha.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>As to that &s;ir, this young lady can inform you I de&s;ired him to leave the hou&s;e an hour ago.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR. <HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm afraid, my only way is to confe&s;s all&mdash;my lord, if I confe&s;s the truth, I hope you'll pre|vail on my aunt to forgive me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell what you know, and I'll an&s;wer for your forgivene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;ir, I found the gentleman alone, and not having had a tete-a-tete a long time, I pre&s;s'd him to &s;tay, and on hearing your voice, I put him behind the &s;opha&mdash;that you might not think any thing had happen|ed&mdash;and indeed &s;ir, nothing did happen&mdash;upon my word he's as quiet an inoffen&s;ive gentleman as your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>My fears are over! Oh you fini&s;hed com|po&s;ition! come to my arms, <STAGE><HI>(embraces)</HI></STAGE> and when I &s;u&s;|pect you again <STAGE><HI>(coughs much)</HI></STAGE> this cur&s;t cough takes one &s;o &s;uddenly!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ENNUI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've an idea, Florivelle is arrived, in fact I ju&s;t now &s;poke to him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Florivelle arrived! Come my lady, let's go and we what his travels have done for him&mdash;hark'ye Ennui&mdash;prepare for your interview with Loui&s;a, and re|member
<PB N="24" REF="24">you make a mandarine member&mdash;come my la|dy&mdash;nay, never irritate your feelings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas my lord! it is the misfortnne of vir|tue to be too feeling for the vices and errors of others&mdash;but I attend you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>So poor Mr Neville is to lo&s;e Mi&s;s Courtney&mdash;her pre&s;ent quarrel with him is &s;o violent, that &s;he may marry this ideot merely in revenge. If I could dupe him now and en&s;ure her contempt. I'll try&mdash;Mr Ennui, have you &s;een your intended wife yet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>No.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I thought&mdash;why you'll never plea&s;e her while you remain as you are&mdash;you mu&s;t alter your man|ners. She's all life&mdash;all &s;pirits! and loves a man the very oppo&s;ite to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've an idea, I'm very &s;orry&mdash;in fact how can I plea&s;e her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's the difficulty, let me &s;ee&mdash;the &s;ort of man &s;he likes&mdash;you know Sir Harry Hu&s;tle&mdash;a man all activity and confidence&mdash;who does every thing from fa&s;hion and glories in confe&s;&s;ing it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Harry Hu&s;tle! In fact he's a modern blood of fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know that's the rea&s;on &s;he likes him, and you mu&s;t bec$me the &s;ame if you wi&s;h to win her affections&mdash;a new dre&s;s, bold looks, a few oaths and much &s;wag|gering effects the bu&s;ine&s;s <STAGE>(Ennui <HI>puts him&s;elf in attitudes</HI>)</STAGE> ay, that's right, you are the very man already!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm a lad of fa&s;hion! hah&mdash;damn me! I've an idea, I &s;hall fall a&s;leep in the mid&s;t of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, go about it directly&mdash;See Sir Harry Hu&s;tle, and &s;tudy your conver&s;ation before-hand&mdash;but re|member Loui&s;a is &s;o &s;ond of fa&s;hion, that you can't boa&s;t too much of its vices and ab&s;urdities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>If virtue was the fa&s;hion, I &s;hou'd be virtuous! I &s;hou'd, damn me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, that's the very thing&mdash;well good b'ye Mr Emmi&mdash;&s;ucce&s; attend you&mdash;mind you talk enough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Talk! I'll talk till I fall a&s;leep! $$$ill, damn me!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Emmi <HI>&s;$$$gg$ring,</HI> Marianne <HI>la$ghing.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="25" REF="25">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A Chamber in <HI>Lady WAITFORT'S</HI> Hou&s;e.&mdash;<HI>LOUISA</HI> di&s;covered reading.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOUISA.</SPEAKER>
<P>HEIGHO! the&s;e poets are wonderfully tire&s;ome&mdash;always on the &s;ame theme&mdash;nothing but love&mdash;I'm weary of it. <STAGE><HI>(Lays down the book and ri&s;es.)</HI></STAGE> Ungenerous Neville! How cou'd he u&s;e me &s;o cruelly? to attempt to gain my affections and then addre&s;s another. Lady Waitfort has convinc'd me of the fact, I can never for|give him, and yet I fear I love him &s;till. Well, I'll e|ven go and examine my heart and determine whether I love him or not.</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>As &s;he is going out</HI> Neville <HI>enters.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr Neville&mdash;I thought &s;ir, I had de&s;ired we might never meet again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis true madam, and I meant to obey your commands hard as they were, implicitly obey them&mdash;but I came here to welcome my brother, and not to in|trude on the happine&s;s of her I am doom'd to avoid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll conceal my embaria&s;&s;ment, I am determin'd. <STAGE><HI>(A&s;ide.)</HI></STAGE> If I remember, &s;ir, truth was ever among the foremo&s;t of your virtues.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>$word$, and I am confident you have no rea&s;on to doubt it&mdash;tho' you have cau&s;e to cen&s;ure my pre&s;ump|tion, you have none to &s;u&s;pect my fidelity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no! I don't &s;u&s;pect your fidelity in the lea&s;t, but when pe$ple are faithful to more than one, you know, Mr Neville.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>I $$n't under&s;tand you ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis no wonder Mr Nevi$$e&mdash;you may &s;pare y$ur&s;elf any $$uble in attempting to ju&s;tify your conduct&mdash;I'm perfectly &s;atisfied &s;ir, I'll a&s;&s;$re you!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Going.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! do not leave me in this anxious &s;tate, per|haps this is $he la&s;t time we &s;hall ever meet; and to part thus wou'd embi$$er every future moment of my life. I indeed have no hopes that concern not your happine&s;s, no wi&s;hes that relate not to your e&s;teem.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="26" REF="26">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I will freely confe&s;s to you, had you &s;hewn the lea&s;t per&s;everance in your affection, or &s;incerity in your behaviour, I cou'd have heard your addre&s;&s;es with plea&s;ure&mdash;but to li&s;ten to them now Mr Neville, wou'd be to approve a conduct my honour prompts me to re|&s;ent, and my pride to de&s;pi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I am lo&s;t indeed! 'tis to the perfidious Lady Waitfort I owe all this&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>Lady</HI> Waitfort <HI>enters behind un&s;een by</HI> Neville)</STAGE>&mdash;my pre&s;ent mi&s;ery, my future pain are all the product of her jealous rage! &s;he is &s;o vile an hypocrite that</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Enter Lady</HI> Waitfort.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is an hypocrite, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is a hypocrite &s;ir, an&s;wer me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>What have you done? look on that lady, ma|dam, there all my hopes and wi&s;hes were combin'd! there was the very &s;ummit of my bli&s;s! I thought I had attained it; but in the moment of my happine&s;s you came, cru&s;h'd every hope and ba&s;&s;ted all my joys!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word &s;ir, very romantic&mdash;but I thank heaven I look for approbation in a better opinion than that of Mr Neville's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well you do madam, for were I your judge, your puni&s;hment &s;hou'd be ex$mplary&mdash;but I'll wa&s;te no more words on you&mdash;I only hope <STAGE>(<HI>to</HI> Loui&s;a)</STAGE> you ma|dam are &s;atisfied that one of my errors may at lea$t be forgiven, and this la&s;t &s;u&s;picion $or ever blotted from your memory.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I'll take care my lord never &s;hall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>N. v.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash; I do not hope for forgivene&s;s&mdash; I have heard her determination, and cruel a$$$t i$$ to that I mu&s;t re|&s;ign&mdash; &s;he may be a&s;&s;ured I never with intrude where I know I offend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you then leave us Mr Neville?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>N$V.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, madam, and for ever! &mdash;may you be as ble&s;t in the gratification of your hopes as I have been wr$tched in the di&s;appointment of mine.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tyrant! I wi&s;h he had &s;tay'd to hear rea|&s;on&mdash;I hope he is not &s;eri$u$ in leaving us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU</SPEAKER>
<P>You hope! &mdash;why does it concern y$u?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! no further than from the general love
<PB N="27" REF="27">I bear mankind&mdash;you forget my feelings on the&s;e occa&s;i|ons, Loui&s;a!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, indeed I have too much rea&s;on to attend my own!&mdash;You'll excu&s;e me&mdash;I have particular bu&s;ine&s;s, but will return immediately.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the cau&s;e of her confu&s;ion is evident&mdash;&s;he loves him &s;till&mdash;but they &s;hall never meet again&mdash;I have already &s;ent a letter to Willoughby, which imparts a &s;cheme I have long cheri&s;hed, my lord in his anger about my &s;$age maniac, has forgot Ennui's play, &s;o that there may be no bars to Willoughby's happine&s;s, I am determined Loui&s;a &s;hall be this very night.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD SCRATCH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a &s;pectacle for a Peer! Florivelle is below, and is re$urn'd from his travels a fini&s;hed cox|comb, I'll not give him a farthing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope not my lord, perhaps you may be mi&s;taken.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;taken! No, he has travell'd not to &s;ee, but to &s;ay he had been &s;een.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARIANNE <HI>(with a French watch and chain.)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh uncle-in-law! look here&mdash;I never &s;aw any &s;o elegant in all my life.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Shewing chain.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who&s;e pre&s;ent is this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR. Who&s;e!</SPEAKER>
<P>why the &s;weet gentleman ju&s;t arri|ved from Italy&mdash;Lord! he's a dear man&mdash;he has pro|mis'd to do every thing for me&mdash;to get me a fortune&mdash;to get me a hu&s;band&mdash;to get me&mdash;a&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h!&mdash;you don't know what you are talking about.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but I do tho', he has told me every thing&mdash;Lord! I have heard &s;uch things! &mdash; come hear&mdash;nearer&mdash;get my aunt out of the room and I'll tell you &s;tories that &s;hall make your old heart bound again!&mdash;hu&s;h do it qui|etly&mdash;I will upon my honour&mdash;what an old fool it is.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;tn't li&s;ten to Mr Florivelle, for tra|vellers may per&s;uade you into any thing, and many a woman has been ruin'd in one country, by being told it is the fa&s;hion in another.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes&mdash;I &s;ee as plain as my peerage I &s;han't keep my temper.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="28" REF="28">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e my lord he has &s;pent great part of his time in France, where he has been the dupe of knaves of every nation.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FLORIVELLE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your pardon madam, you wrong the French&mdash;they never &s;uffer any one to dupe a traveller but them|&s;elves&mdash;ladies a thou&s;and pardons for not waiting on you before; but this is the fir&s;t vacant moment I have had &s;ince my arrival at Bath.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your coming at all is taken as a very great compliment I'll a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT. (<HI>To</HI> Marianne <HI>who exits.</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash; Leave the room immediately&mdash;no reply &mdash; I will be obey'd&mdash;Mr Florivelle, we are very happy to &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am you do me honour&mdash;my lord where's Harry? I thought to have found him here&mdash;what, he didn't chu&s;e to &s;tay&mdash;&s;o much the better&mdash;it &s;hews he's not a man of ceremony&mdash;we do the &s;ame in Italy&mdash;but hark'ye.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>My gorge is ri&s;ing! I &s;hall certainly do him a mi&s;chief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. (<HI>Spying at Lady</HI> Waitfort)</SPEAKER>
<P>Rather experienc'd or &s;o&mdash;a little antique hah!&mdash;however, the &s;ame motive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, from that lady's forgivene&s;s you have nothing to expect&mdash;If &s;he con&s;ents to pardon you, that which makes her a good aunt to me, will make her a good wife to you&mdash;you under&s;tand me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn me if I do!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, no matter&mdash;come come, I want to hear every thing, to know what remarkable occurrences have happen'd &s;ince I left England&mdash;pray Lady Wait|fort inform me&mdash;do let me know every little circum&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rather &s;ir, we &s;hould a&s;k of you, what hap|pen'd in your travels?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh nothing &s;o &s;hocking&mdash;no man can be the herald of his own prai&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, but I wi&s;h to know how you like the chapel of Loretto, the Venus de Medicis of Florence, the Natican at Rome, and all the numberle&s;s curio&s;ities peculiar to the countries you have travell'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye&mdash;I'll an&s;wer for it, he knows
<PB N="29" REF="29">nothing of the gentlemen you mention&mdash;do you my &s;weet pretty&mdash;oh you damn'd puppy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why &s;wear my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Swear my lord! zounds! its my pre|rogative and by&mdash;tell me how you &s;pent your time, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why in contemplating living angels, not dead antiquities! in ba&s;king in the rays of beauty! not moul|dering in the du&s;t of <HI>ance&s;try!</HI> in mirth, fe&s;tivity and plea&s;ure! not &s;tudy, pedantry, and retirement&mdash;oh I have lived &s;ir! lived for my&s;elf, not an ungrateful world, who, &s;hou'd I die a martyr for their cau&s;e, wou'd only laugh and wonder at my folly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;eem to know the world Mr Florivelle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No madam, I know little of mankind, and le&s;s of my&s;elf&mdash;I have no pilot but my plea&s;ures! no mi&s;tre&s;s but my pa&s;&s;ions! and I don't believe if it were to &s;ave my life I cou'd rea&s;on con&s;equently for a minute toge|ther.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Granted&mdash;you have &s;een every thing worth &s;eeing, yet know nothing worth knowing, and af|ter all you have ju&s;t knowledge enough to prove your&s;elf a fool on every &s;ubject.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Va&s;tly well my lord, upon my word you im|prove with your title; but I am perfectly &s;atisfied believe me; for what I don't know, I take for granted is not worth knowing&mdash;therefore we'll call another topic, I'm in love my lord!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>In love!&mdash;with who &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you gue&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;ir, I cannot!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>With one that will plea&s;e you very much&mdash;at lea&s;t ought to plea&s;e you&mdash;you'll be in raptures dear un|cle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Raptures;&mdash;and you &s;hall be in agonies my dear nephew!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have known one another a long while, yet you hav'nt met for years&mdash;you have lov'd one another a long while, yet you quarrel'd not an hour ago, you have differ'd from one another all your lives, yet are likely to be friends as long as you live, and above all, this per&s;on is now in this hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="30" REF="30">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>In this hou&s;e! tell me who it is this mo|ment, or by the blood of the Scratches!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>One who has charms enough to &s;et the world on fire! one who has fortune enough to &s;et a &s;tate at war &s;ir! one who has talents, health and pro&s;perity, and yet not half what the party de&s;erves&mdash;can you tell now &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir, and if you don't tell this in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FROR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll tell you. Its my&s;elf, &s;ir&mdash;my own charming &s;elf!&mdash;I've &s;earch'd the world over, and don't find any thing I like half &s;o well.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Walks up the &s;tage.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I won't di&s;grace my&s;elf&mdash;I won't lower the dignity of peerage by cha&s;ti&s;ing a commoner, el&s;e you prince of butterflies&mdash;come my lady&mdash;look'ye &s;ir&mdash;I intend to be handed down to po&s;terity; and while you are lampoon'd in ballads and news-papers, I mean to cut a figure in the hi&s;tory of England&mdash;&s;o come along my lady&mdash;in the hi&s;tory of England! you damn'd cox|comb.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>If the face be a picture of the mind, that in|tended aunt of mine is a great hypocrite, and the &s;tory I heard of the poet proves it&mdash;but now for a frolic&mdash;'gad its very &s;trange I cou'd never reform and become a &s;eri|ous thinking being! but what's the u&s;e of thinking?</P>
<Q><L>"Rea&s;on &s;tays till we call, then not oft is near,</L>
<L>"But hone&s;t in&s;tinct comes a volunteer."</L></Q>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A Chamber in Lady <HI>WAITFORT'S.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WILLOUGHBY <HI>and</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell your mi&s;tre&s;s I &s;hall be punctual to the appointment. <STAGE>(<HI>Exit</HI> Servant.)</STAGE> So thanks to fortune, Lady Waitfort has at la&s;t con&s;ented to my entreaties, and this night makes Loui&s;a mine for ever!&mdash;now to read the letter once more&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(Reads)</HI></STAGE> <Q>Loui&s;a accompa|nies &startq;me to night to Lady Walton's, which you know is at the extremity of the town&mdash;on &s;ome pre&s;ence or other, I'll tell her I have order'd the &s;ervant at the back gate, which adjoins the paddock&mdash;there I'll leave her, and if you have a chai&s;e waiting near the &s;pot you may conduct her where you plea&s;e, you know my feelings on this occa&s;ion, but it is for her good only I'll a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;&s;he don't de&s;erve it Mr Willoughby:&mdash;Indeed &endq;&s;he don't de&s;erve it. A. Waitfort!</Q></P>
<PB N="31" REF="31">
<P>So! this is beyond my hopes&mdash;Ha! my lord! and Loui&s;a with him! come to receive Ennui, whom to my a&s;|toni&s;hment I met ju&s;t now in a new dre&s;s, &s;wearing and capering, and boa&s;ting of the vices of fa&s;hion, but no matter&mdash;I mu&s;t to the rendezvous immediately. Now Loui&s;a, tremble at my vengeance.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lord SCRATCH <HI>and</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, Ennui will be here in an in|&s;tant, but he's &s;o re&s;erv'd, and &s;o mild.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I under&s;tand &s;ir, and &s;o very &s;ilent that he won't talk &s;o much in a year as I intend in an hour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know that's the rea&s;on I bring him in|to Parliament&mdash;he'll never &s;peak&mdash;only &s;ay aye, or no, and be up &s;tairs to Beef &s;takes in an in&s;tant. <STAGE><HI>(Knock.)</HI></STAGE> Here he is?&mdash;now encourage him Loui&s;a, don't mind his diffidence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;ir,&mdash;I'll do all in my power to make him talk.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's well,&mdash;I'll leave you together&mdash;I don't interrupt you. <STAGE><HI>(Stamping without)</HI></STAGE> od&s;o, I mu&s;t get out of the way&mdash;encourage him Loui&s;a, I be&s;eech you encourage him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN. <HI>(without)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stand by no ceremony, damn me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens! is this diffidence!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ENNUI <HI>and</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get down &s;tairs you dog&mdash;get down&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>Exit</HI> Servant)</STAGE>&mdash;Here I am ma'am&mdash;ea&s;e is every thing&mdash;I'll feat my&s;elf&mdash;now for bu&s;ine&s;s,&mdash;Yaw, yaw.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Yawns a&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>In one word ma'am, I'll tell you my character&mdash;I'm a lad of fa&s;hion dam'me, I love gaming, I hate thinking&mdash;I like railing&mdash;I de&s;pi&s;e reading&mdash;I patronize boxing&mdash;I dete&s;t rea&s;oning&mdash;I pay debts of honour&mdash;not honourable debts.&mdash;In &s;hort I'll kick your &s;ervant&mdash;cheat your family, and fight your guardian&mdash;and &s;o if you like me take&mdash;heh, damn me&mdash;I'm tired already&mdash;yaw&mdash;yaw?&mdash;yawns.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;toni&s;hing! Mr Ennui.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am, yaw&mdash;yaw&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr Ennui! Can you be in your &s;en&s;es?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>In fact I don't comprehend, <STAGE><HI>(forgetting him&s;elf)</HI></STAGE>
<PB N="32" REF="32">Oh! ay&mdash;&s;en&s;es <STAGE><HI>(recollecting him&s;elf,)</HI></STAGE>&mdash;a lad of fa&s;hion in his &s;en&s;es! that's a very good joke&mdash;if one of us had any &s;en&s;e, the re&s;t would &s;hut him up in a cabinet of cu|rio&s;ities, or &s;hew him for a wonderful animal! they wou'd damn me; I can't &s;upport it&mdash;yaw&mdash;yaw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you glory in your ignorance&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am, yaw&mdash;yaw!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>So you glory in your ignorance&mdash;in your vices.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've an idea&mdash;I can't under&s;tand <STAGE><HI>(forgetting him|&s;elf)</HI></STAGE> vices&mdash;Oh&mdash;ay damn me to be &s;ure! <STAGE><HI>(recollecting him&s;elf)</HI></STAGE> You mu&s;t be wicked or you can't be vi&s;ited&mdash;&s;ingularity is every thing&mdash;notoriety&mdash;every man mu&s;t get a character&mdash;and I'll tell you how I fir&s;t got mine. I pretended to intrigue with my friend's wife&mdash;para|graph'd my&s;elf in the new&s;papers&mdash;got caricatured in the print &s;hops&mdash;made the &s;tory believed, was abu&s;ed by every body&mdash;noticed for my gallantry by every body, and at length vi&s;ited by every body&mdash;I was, damn me! <STAGE><HI>(I'm cur&s;t &s;leepy)</HI></STAGE> yaw, yaw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Incredible! but if &s;ingularity be your &s;y&s;tem, perhaps being virtuous wou'd make you as particular as any thing</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Va&s;tly well! Egad you're like me&mdash;a wit and don't know it <STAGE><HI>(takes out his watch)</HI></STAGE> how goes the enemy? more than half the day over! tol de rol lol, <STAGE><HI>(&s;inging)</HI></STAGE> I am as happy as if I was at a fire, or a general riot&mdash;Come to my arms thou angel! thou&mdash; <STAGE>(<HI>as he is going to embrace her, enter</HI> LORD SCRATCH <HI>who catches him.</HI>)</STAGE> Ah Scratch! my friend Scratch! &s;it down my old boy, &s;it down, we've fettled every thing</P>
<STAGE><HI>(forces him into a chair.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why! what is all this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's to intrigue&mdash;and you and I are to go halves in the damages&mdash;&s;ome rich old Nabob&mdash;we'll draw him into crim con! bring an action directly&mdash;and get a 10,000 <ABBR>l.</ABBR> verdict at lea&s;t, heh! damn me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why he's mad. That dramatic Mani|ac has bit him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get a divorce&mdash;marry another, and go halves again damn me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why look'ye, you impo&s;tor you, didn't you come here to pay your addre&s;&s;es to this lady&mdash;and
<PB N="33" REF="33">wasn't I to bring you into parliament for your quiet, &s;i|lent di&s;po&s;ition?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN. <HI>(Pu&s;hing him out of the way.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue! out of the way Scratch, out of the way! or I'll do you a mi&s;chief damn me! Zounds! ai'nt I at the top of the beau monde? and don't I lead the fa&s;hion? If I was to cut off my head wou'dnt half the town do the &s;ame, they wou'd damn me. I get &s;leepy again, yaw&mdash;yaw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here now, here's a mandarine member, why he'd breed a civil war! make ten long &s;peeches in a day! Cut your head off indeed! Cur&s;e me but I wi&s;h it was cut off&mdash;you mu&s;t be &s;ilent then&mdash;you can't talk without a head cou'd you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, in <HI>parliament,</HI> as well without a head as with one&mdash;do you think a man wants a head to make a long &s;peech damn me?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SERVANT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SERV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her lady&s;hip is waiting ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Serv.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh: I attend her, Mr Ennui, your mo&s;t obedi|ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN. <HI>(Taking her hand.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>With your leave ma'am, you &s;ee Scratch&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why Loui&s;a!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep your di&s;tance Scratch&mdash;contemplate your &s;uperi$rs&mdash;look at me with the &s;ame awful re&s;pect as city beaus look at a prince&mdash;this way mo&s;t angelico&mdash;Scratch, cut off your head&mdash;this way mo&s;t divine angelico.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Ennui <HI>and</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's treatment! Was ever a poor peer &s;o tormented&mdash;what am I to do? I'll go to Lady Wait|fort, for from her alone I meet relief&mdash;find a &s;ilent mem|ber indeed! by my peerage and privilege one might as &s;oon find a pin in the ocean, as charity in a bench of Bi|&s;hops, or wit in We&s;tmin&s;ter Hall.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="34" REF="34">
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<HEAD>SCENE&mdash;<HI>Paddock near</HI> Lady WAITFORT<HI>'S hou&s;e.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WILLOUGHBY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILLOUGHBY.</SPEAKER>
<P>'TIS pa&s;t the hour Lady Waitfort appointed&mdash;Why does &s;he delay? I cannot have mi&s;taken the place&mdash;yonder is Lady Walton's hou&s;e! Oh would all were pa&s;t, and Loui&s;a &s;afely mine: I hear a noi&s;e! by Hea|ven's 'tis &s;he, and with her all my happine&s;s&mdash;I'll with|draw a while and ob&s;erve them.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Retires.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> WAITFORT <HI>and</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Lady Waitfort, why do you loiter here? You cannot find your &s;ervant in this place, let us return to Lady Walton's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, they mu&s;t be here, I order'd them to wait in this very &s;pot to avoid confu&s;ion.&mdash;What can have become of Willoughby?</P>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>If you have the lea&s;t &s;en&s;e of fear for your&s;elf, or regard for me, I beg we may return to Lady Walton's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, I order'd William at the back gate that he might conduct us through the paddock to our carriage, you know we might have been whole hours getting thro' the crowd the other way, do be a little pa|tient, hav'nt I as much rea&s;on to be alarm'd as your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but you hav'nt the apprehen&s;ion that I have, I don't know why, but I am terrified beyond de&s;cription!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, never fear, <STAGE><HI>(looking out)</HI></STAGE> Oh, yonder's Willoughby! now for the grand de&s;ign! <STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></STAGE> if you'll &s;tay here a moment, I'll &s;tep to the next gate and &s;ee if they are there&mdash;they cannot e&s;cape us then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no! don't leave me! I wouldn't &s;tay by my&s;elf for the world!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ridiculous! can't you protect your&s;elf for an in&s;tant? Mu&s;t you be all your life watched like a baby in leading &s;trings? Oh! I'm a&s;ham'd of you, only wait
<PB N="35" REF="35">a moment, le&s;t they pa&s;s by in my ab&s;ence, and I'll re|turn to you immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well don't &s;tay!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay! What have you to be frightened at? I &s;hall not be out of call, be&s;ides if there's any $ear of a per&s;onal attack, may not I be as terrified as your&s;elf. It is'nt the fir&s;t time I'll a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;but that's no mat|ter, &s;hew your&s;elf a woman of &s;pirit, and at lea&s;t emu|late one of my virtues&mdash;now Willoughby the re&s;t is thine</P>
<STAGE><HI>(a&s;ide)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Lady</HI> Waitfort.</STAGE>
<STAGE>WILLOUGHBY <HI>comes forward.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be not alarm'd Mi&s;s Courtney!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr Willoughby!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes madam, the man you mo&s;t avoid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell me &s;ir immediately how, and by who&s;e ap|pointment you came here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>By love madam, the &s;ame pa&s;&s;ion that has prompted me to pur&s;ue you for years, now happily con|ducts me hither&mdash;I come to le&s;&s;en your fears, not to en|crea&s;e them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then leave me &s;ir, I can protect my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, not till you have heard and pitied me&mdash;I have been long your &s;uitor, and long &s;corn'd by you&mdash;you have treated me with indifference, and preferr'd my inferiors&mdash;how I have de&s;erv'd all this, your&s;elf can be&s;t explain; but to prove all former cruelties are forgot, I here offer you my hand and with it my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, this is no time for hearing you on this &s;ub|ject, it you wi&s;h to oblige me, leave me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, not till I am an&s;wer'd&mdash;years may elap&s;e e're I &s;hall have another opportunity like the pre&s;ent, therefore no time can be &s;o well as now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, I command you to leave me, I will not be threatened into a compliance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye, Mi&s;s Courtney, I wou'd avoid taking advantage of your &s;ituation&mdash;nay &s;tart not&mdash;but if you per&s;i&s;t in your contempt of me, I know not to what extre|mities pa&s;&s;ion may hurry me, I have every motive for redre&s;s, a d$f you do not in&s;tantly give me your word to prefer me to that beggar Neville, I may do that my cooler &s;en&s;e would &s;corn.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="36" REF="36">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beggar &s;ir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and were he not beneath my re&s;entment, I'd tell you more&mdash;but he's too poor&mdash;too&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold &s;ir, did you re&s;emble him, I might e&s;teem, nay adore you; you take advantage of my &s;ituation; hear me &s;ir! tho' not a friend is near, tho' night oppo|&s;es me, and Heaven de&s;erts me, yet can I &s;mile upon your menaces, for my own eyes &s;hall vindicate my wrongs, and make you tremble villain, as you are!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have a care madam, another declaration like that, and I'll delay no longer, I'll force you to my pur|po&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>You dare not, on your life you dare not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then, I'm not to be terrified by threats&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(lays hold of her)</HI></STAGE> all &s;truggling is in vain, this moment gratifies my revenge! away.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Off&mdash;let me go, Oh help! help!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(As he is for|cing her out, enters</HI> FLORIVELLE <HI>half drunk.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. <HI>(Singing part of an Italian Song.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Donne, don|ne, don&mdash;Oh this burgundy's a glorious liquor&mdash;hey day! who have we here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh &s;ir, if you have any pity for an injur'd help|le&s;s woman, a&s;&s;i&s;t one who never knew di&s;tre&s;s till now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on ma'am, go on! both damned drunk I perceive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not &s;ir be deaf to my intreaties, do not de|&s;ert me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go on madam, go on&mdash;I love oratory in a wo|man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gracious Heaven! how have I de&s;erved this? I &s;ee &s;ir you avoid me&mdash;I &s;ee you're indifferent to my fate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No ma'am, you wrong me&mdash;but in Italy ob|&s;erve we always take the&s;e things coolly&mdash;now &s;ir <STAGE>(<HI>to</HI> Willoughby)</STAGE> will you explain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;ir, I will not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;ir, and I warn you not to li&s;ten to the wild ravings of a &s;en&s;ele&s;s woman&mdash;it may be better for you &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="37" REF="37">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o, Prince Prettyman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter &s;ir, I will not be amu&s;ed from my purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>You won't old Pluto, won't you! then ma'am ob&s;erve, you &s;hall behold my mode of fighting&mdash;I'll kill him like a gentleman, and he &s;hall die without a groan &mdash;you'll be delighted ma'am&mdash;I learn't it all in Italy&mdash; you don't &s;ee a man of fa&s;hion fight once in a century! Come Beelzebub are you ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath what can I do? he is drunk perhaps, I may di&s;arm him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now thou original &s;in! Thou Prince of Dark|ne&s;s! come out, never let her &s;ee thy black infernal vi|&s;age more, or by my life I'll pulveri&s;e you! You &s;ee ma'am no bad orator either&mdash;learnt it all in Italy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come on &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay now old Sy&s;ippus pu&s;h home&mdash;but do you hear, fight like a gentleman, for remember there's a la|dy in company. Ob&s;erve ma'am, ob&s;erve! you won't &s;ee it again! <STAGE>(<HI>They fight,</HI> Florivelle <HI>di&s;arms him</HI>).</STAGE> What vanqui&s;h'd Tarquin! Hah! <STAGE><HI>(parrying up and down the &s;tage in triumph.)</HI></STAGE> You &s;ee ma'am, you fee&mdash;Oh Italy's your own country! Now madam, wou'd you have me kill him here "en allegro," or po&s;tpone it, that you may have the plea&s;ure of pinking him your&s;elf "en pen&s;eroro."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Florivelle my deliverer! Generous man! No, &s;ir, whatever are his crimes do not kill him&mdash;his greate&s;t pu|ni&s;hment will be to live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>There then Caitiff, take your &s;word, and d'ye hear&mdash;retire&mdash;that black face of thine offends the lady&mdash; if you want another flouri&s;h you will &s;oon find Florivelle &mdash;Ab&s;cond!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, you &s;hall &s;oon hear from me&mdash;Di&s;traction!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now my dear little angel! how can I a&s;|&s;i&s;t you? I'm very &s;orry but I cannot help it&mdash;I'm cur&s;t drunk and not proper company for a lady of your dignity&mdash;but I won't affront you, I mean to make my|&s;elf agreeable, and if I do not it is the fault of this place <STAGE><HI>(pointing to his head)</HI></STAGE> and not this <STAGE><HI>(pointing to his heart.)</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your conduct has endear'd you to me for
<PB N="38" REF="38">ever, and while I live, your genero&s;ity and valour &s;hall be engraven on my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gently, gently, have a care, make no declara|rations &mdash;if you are in love with me, as I &s;uppo&s;e you are, keep it a &s;ecret, for at this moment you might rai&s;e a flame that wou'd con&s;ume us both, poor creature! how fond &s;he is of me, any other time I wou'd indulge her, but not now <STAGE><HI>(looks at her, and then runs and ki&s;&s;es her hand.)</HI></STAGE> Oh you paragon! "Angels mu&s;t paint to look as fair as you," <STAGE><HI>(goes from her again)</HI></STAGE> I'll leave you, or by Heavens! it will be all over with us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, don't de&s;ert me, alas I have no way left, but to commit my&s;elf to your care. If I cou'd bring him to recollect me all wou'd be &s;afe&mdash;Mr Flori|velle, don't you know me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;would to Heaven I did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, not Mi&s;s Courtney?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>What Loui&s;a! my brother's idol?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>The very &s;ame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then may I die, if I don't get out of your debt before I leave you&mdash;where, where &s;hall I conduct you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! I know not&mdash;return to Lady Waitfort's I will not, I had rather be a wanderer all my life&mdash;to Lady Walton's there is no excu&s;e for my returning. I know no friend in Bath I dare intrude upon&mdash;I have &s;o high an opinion Mr Florivelle of your honour, that not|with&s;tanding your pre&s;ent &s;ituation, there is no man on earth I wou'd &s;ooner confide in, can you then think of any place where I may re&s;t in &s;afety for a few hours; and then I will &s;et out for my uncle's in the country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I cannot, I am a wanderer my&s;elf&mdash;I have no hou&s;e, but what this gentleman is to purcha&s;e me <STAGE><HI>(taking out his pur&s;e)</HI></STAGE> You cannot partake of that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh what will become of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me &s;ee&mdash;I have it&mdash;I'll take her to my bro|ther's &mdash;&s;he'll be &s;afe there and not a &s;oul &s;hall come near her&mdash;well Mi&s;s Courtney, I have recollected a place where I know you'll be &s;afe&mdash;a friend's hou&s;e that will be as &s;e|cure &mdash;nay, don't droop, in Italy never, never melancholy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mr Florivelle! to what a hazard has Lady
<PB N="39" REF="39">Waitfort expos'd me&mdash;to her perfidy I owe it all&mdash;but yonder's that wretch again, pray let us begone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beelzebub again? no, no&mdash;mu&s;tn't &s;tir&mdash;what an angel fly from a devil! I'll &s;tay and cru&s;h him, Tar|quin avaunt! come my be&s;t angel! I'll fight your bat|tles, and if I don't &s;ink all your enemies, may I never &s;ee Italy again as long as I live.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WILLOUGHBY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WILL.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! gone! I'm &s;orry for it&mdash;I wou'd have &s;een them, Lady Waitfort has ju&s;t left me and treated me like her &s;lave&mdash;in&s;ulted and derided me&mdash;but I'll have done with her for ever&mdash;I'll be her dupe no more&mdash;She is now gone to Neville's lodgings under pretence of pur&s;uing Loui&s;a; but in fact to &s;ee him, and prevent his leaving Bath; thus I hope I &s;hall make &s;ome reparations for the wrongs I have committed, and prove at lea&s;t that I have &s;ome virtue.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE&mdash;NEVILLE'S <HI>Lodgings.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> VAPID <HI>and</HI> PETER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, here it is&mdash;where's Neville?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not within &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, here it is&mdash;I mu&s;t &s;ee him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir he's gone out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gone out! impo&s;&s;ible!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible! it's very true &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gone out! why I have brought him the epilogue &mdash;the new epilogue to Mr What's his name's comedy&mdash; the very be&s;t thing I ever wrote in my life&mdash;I knew it wou'd delight him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, he has been gone out above the&s;e two hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then he'll never forgive him&s;elf as long as he lives&mdash;why its all correct&mdash;all cha&s;te! only one half line wanting at the end to make it compleat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed &s;ir, its very unfortunate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unfortunate! I wanted to have heard him read it too, when another per&s;on reads it, one often hits on a thought that might have otherwi&s;e e&s;caped, then per|haps he wou'd have hit on that curs'd half line I've &s;o long been working at.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, if it is not impertinent, and you'd permit me to read it&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>You read it!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="40" REF="40">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, if you'd allow me the honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh! Why faith I wou'd have no objection&mdash; but then wou'dn't it le&s;&s;en one's dignity! no, no, Moliere u&s;ed to read his plays to his &s;ervant&mdash;&s;o I believe all's regular&mdash;but &s;ir, can you read! come then begin.</P>
<STAGE>Peter <HI>reads the Epilogue.</HI>
<L>"In ancient times when agoni&s;ing wars,</L>
<L>"And bleeding nations fill'd the world with jars,</L>
<L>"When murder, battle, &s;udden death prevail'd</L>
<L>"When!&mdash;</L></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, &s;top! I have it&mdash;not a word for your life &mdash;I feel it&mdash;its coming on! the la&s;t line directly&mdash;quick, quick&mdash;
<STAGE>Peter <HI>reads,</HI>
<L>"The tyrant totters and the &s;enate nods,</L>
<L>"Die all, die nobly&mdash;</L></STAGE> here's &s;omething wanting &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it, &s;ay nothing&mdash;I have it <STAGE><HI>(walking up and down the &s;tage.)</HI>
<L>"The tyrant totters and the &s;enate nods,</L>
<L>"Die all, die nobly!&mdash;</L></STAGE> Oh damn it! damn it! damn it! that curs'd half line&mdash; I &s;hall never accompli&s;h it&mdash;all &s;o cha&s;te&mdash;all &s;o correct&mdash; and to have it marr'd for wanting one half line! one cur&s;t half line! vexatious! I cou'd almo&s;t weep for di&s;|appointment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never mind it &s;ir, don't perplex your&s;elf, put in any thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Put in any thing! why you damned dog what do you mean&mdash;put in any thing, why you ra&s;eal, 'tis the la&s;t line, and the $pilogue mu&s;t end with &s;omething &s;tri|king or it will be no trap for the galleries, no trap for applau&s;e after all this &s;ine writing! Oh, 'tis too much!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Methinks this is a &s;trange Epilogue for a Co|medy. Perhaps this is my ma&s;ter &s;ir, no as I live, 'tis Mr Florivelle and Mi&s;s Courtney&punc; She mu&s;tn't on any account be &s;een by this gentleman.</P>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, who is it?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="41" REF="41">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir it's a friend of my ma&s;ter's who has brought a lady with him&mdash;I'm &s;ure you've too much gallantry to interrupt an amour, and therefore you'll be kind enough to get out of the way directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Get out of the way? What the devil in the mid|dle of my compo&s;ition?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay &s;ir, only &s;tep for a moment into that clo&s;et, and you &s;hall &s;oon be releas'd&mdash;now pray &s;ir, be pre|vail'd on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, let me &s;ee, in this clo&s;et! why you damn'd dog! this is a china clo&s;et! wou'd you ram a live author into a china clo&s;et?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can I do &s;ir, there is no other way out but that door&mdash;do &s;ir, get in here, for an in&s;tant, and I'll &s;hew them into the library&mdash;now &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, be brief then&mdash;"Die all&mdash;die nobly!" Oh, Oh, Oh!</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Goes into the clo&s;et.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FLORIVELLE <HI>and</HI> LOUISA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey day! my old acquaintance Peter! where's my brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, he has been out the whole evening.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the &s;ame hou&s;e with Neville, Oh Heavens!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well now Mi&s;s Courtney I hope you're con|vinc'd of your &s;afety?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, but I wou'd it were in any other place: Lady Waitfort e're this is in pur&s;uit of me, and if &s;he di&s;covers me here, you know too well how much I have to dread.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarm'd, there's nothing &s;hall mole&s;t you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;ir! you don't know the endle&s;s malice of Lady Waitfort&mdash;&s;he will triumph in my mi&s;ery, and, till my lord is convinc'd of her duplicity, I &s;ee no hopes of your brother's happine&s;s or my own.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> PETER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lady Waitfort is below &s;ir, enquiring for that lady, or my ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>For my brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, and my lord has &s;ent to know if her lady&s;hip or Mr Vapid has been here. He was in bed, but on receiving a letter, got up, and will be here in an in&s;tant.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="42" REF="42">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>For Heaven's &s;ake Mr Florivelle, let me retire I cannot &s;upport the conflict.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prom$$$ to recal your &s;pirits and you &s;hall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>What I can do I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then know no apprehen&s;ions, for on my life you &s;hall not be di&s;turb'd.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Leads her to the door of the library and talks in dumb &s;hew.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP, <HI>(from the clo&s;et)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Peter, Peter, can't you relea&s;e me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir, don't move, you'll ruin every thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then give me that candle &mdash; I've got a pen and ink, and I think I can fini&s;h my Epilogue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;ir,</P>
<STAGE><HI>(giving the candle.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>That cur&s;t half line, "Die all&mdash;die nobly!"</P>
<STAGE>(Peter <HI>&s;huts him in.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. <HI>(&s;its at table and drinks</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>So now the &s;torm be|gins, and I'll have &s;ome &s;port with the enemy&mdash;here &s;he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LADY WAITFORT.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Chairs Peter&mdash;chairs! &s;it down Ma'am, you honour ma exceedingly.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where's your brother &s;ir, I in&s;i&s;t on &s;eeing him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD SCRATCH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>There &s;he is, in a man's lodgings at midnight! here's treatment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord I came here in &s;earch of Loui&s;a, who has been betray'd from my power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRARCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye my lady read that letter, and then &s;ay if we &s;han't both cut a figure in the print &s;hops.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT. <HI>(taking the letter.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! 'tis Willougby's hand! reads, "Lady Waitfort, I have only time to tell you, is gone to Neville's lodgings, to meet a per&s;on &s;he has long had a pa&s;&s;ion for, follow her and be convinced of her duplicity." Oh the villain! Well my lord, and pray who is the man I came to meet?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why who &s;hou'd it be but the &s;tage ruffian, if there was a &s;opha in the room, my word on't he'd pop from behind it&mdash;Zounds that fellow will lay &s;traw at my door every nine months.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is fortunate <STAGE><HI>[a&s;ide]</HI></STAGE> well, &s;ir, if I di&s;|cover Loui&s;a, I hope you'll be convinced I came here to
<PB N="45" REF="43">redeem her&mdash;and not di&s;grace my&s;elf. Tell me &s;ir, im|mediately, where &s;he's conceal'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sit down ma'am, &s;it down&mdash;drink&mdash;drink, then we'll talk over the whole affair&mdash;there is no doing bu&s;i|ne&s;s without wine&mdash;come "here's the glory of gallantry" I'm &s;ure you'll both drink that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No trifling &s;ir,&mdash;tell me where &s;he is con|cealed&mdash;nay then I'll examine the apartments my&s;elf&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(goes to the door of the library)</HI></STAGE> the door lock'd, give me the key, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. <HI>(drinking.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The glory of gallantry!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me &s;ir, if the lady is in that apart|ment, I &s;hall be convinc'd that you and your brother are the &s;ole authors of all this treachery&mdash;if &s;he is there&mdash;by the honour of my ance&s;tors &s;he &s;hall be Willoughby's wife to-morrow morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. <HI>(Ri&s;ing)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Shall &s;he my Lord! pray were you ever in Italy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRAICH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why? Coxcomb?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I'm afraid you have been bitten by a tarantula&mdash;you'll excu&s;e me but the &s;ymptoms are won|derfully alarming! there is a blazing fury in your eye, a wild emotion in your countenance, and a green &s;pot on your no&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn the green &s;pot! open that door immediately&mdash;I am a Peer, and have a right to look at every thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. <HI>(&s;tanding before the door.)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No &s;ir, this door mu&s;t not be open'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll forget my peerage and draw my &s;word</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR (<HI>To Lady</HI> Waitfort <HI>who is going to interfere,</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>don't be alarm'd ma'am&mdash;I'll indulge him for my own amu&s;ement&mdash;mere trout fi&s;hing to me ma'am&mdash;come my lord, I'll give you a &s;pecimen of foreign gladiator&s;hip, and you &s;hall confe&s;s that F$orivelle is the be&s;t fencer in Europe, don't be alarm'd ma'am, come on.</P>
<STAGE>&mdash; (Loui&s;a <HI>right from the apartment.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>$word$! I charge you hold, let not my unhappy fate be the &s;ource of more calamities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis &s;he her&s;elf! my lady did not come to meet the madman!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="46" REF="44">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the lord, ma'am, you've ruin'd all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know, &s;ir, the con&s;equences of this di&s;covery and I abide by them&mdash;but what I have done I can ju&s;ti|fy, and would to heaven all here could do the &s;ame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I can't tell&mdash;I wi&s;h I was in Italy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mark me madam, nay tears are in vain, to-morrow &s;hall make you the wife of Willoughby, and he &s;hall an&s;wer for your follies&mdash;no reply&mdash;&s;ir, <STAGE>(<HI>to</HI> Flo|rivelle, <HI>who is going to &s;peak</HI>)</STAGE> I wou'dnt hear the lord Chancellor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now who is to blame? Oh virtue is ever &s;ure to meet its reward! come to meet a mad poet in|deed! my Lord, I forgive you only on condition of your &s;igning a contract to marry me to-morrow, and Loui&s;a and Willoughby at the &s;ame time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will thou be&s;t of women!&mdash;draw it up immediately, and Neville &s;hall &s;tarve for his treachery</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>Lady</HI> Wait&s;ort <HI>goes to the table and writes.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU. (<HI>falling at Lord</HI> Scratch's <HI>feet.</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me &s;ir, not for my&s;elf but a wrong'd friend I &s;peak&mdash;Mr Neville knows not of my concealment, on my honour; he is in|nocent. If that lady's wrongs be aveng'd, confine the puni&s;hment to me&mdash;I'll bear it; with patience bear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let go&mdash;let go I &s;ay! my gorge is ri|&s;ing again&mdash;Lady Waitfort make ha&s;te with the contract.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>It only wants the &s;ignature&mdash;now my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye my Lord!&mdash;&s;he is the cau&s;e of all this mi&s;chief, and if you are not lo&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out of my way&mdash;noi&s;e and non&s;en&s;e!&mdash; don't fancy your&s;elf in the Hou&s;e of Commons&mdash;We're not &s;peaking twenty at a time, here give me the pen&mdash; I'll &s;ign directly, and now&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>As be is going to &s;ign,</HI> Vapid <HI>breaks china in the clo&s;et, and ru&s;hes out with the Epilogue in his hand.</HI>(</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Die all! die nobly! die like demi Gods&mdash;Huz|za, huzza, 'tis pa&s;t, 'tis done! 'tis perfect.</P>
<STAGE><HI>(Jumps a|bout the &s;tage with extravagant tokens of joy.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza! the mad poet at la&s;t, &s;top him, who can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confu&s;ion! tell me &s;ir immediately, what do you mean by this new in&s;ult?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Die all! die nobly!&mdash;die like demi Gods!&mdash;Oh 'tis glorious!&mdash;ah, old Scratch are you there! Joy, joy!
<PB N="47" REF="45">give me joy! I've done your bu&s;ine&s;s, the work's pa&s;t, the labour's o'er my boy&mdash;think of that ma&s;ter Brook, think of that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I'm vilely treated, I de&s;ire you'll in&s;i&s;t on an explanation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>He can't &s;peak ma'am,</P>
<STAGE><HI>(all this time pa&s;t my Lord is &s;lowly walking away.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;are you going to leave me my lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>Taking out his common-place book.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Faith this mu&s;tn't be lo&s;t&mdash;here's &s;omething worth ob&s;erving.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FROR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;top him, ma'am&mdash;in every furrow of his angry brow is written "frailty, thy name is woman" &mdash;let him have his way.&mdash;See how &s;olemnly he re|tires.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit Lord</HI> Scratch.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I &s;hall bur&s;t with rage! Mr Vapid, I de&s;ire you'll explain how you came into that clo&s;et? why don't you an&s;wer me, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your pardon ma'am, I am taking a note of the whole affair&mdash;and yet I'm afraid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are you afraid of, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>That it has been dramatiz'd before&mdash;it is cer|tainly not a new ca&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;upportable! but I take my leave of you all&mdash;I abandon you for ever&mdash;I&mdash;oh! I &s;hall go wild.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Exit in a rage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay follow his Lord&s;hip, "virtue is ever &s;ure to meet its reward."&mdash;Now, Mr Vapid, pray tell us how you came into that clo&s;et?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my &s;oul I can't&mdash;I believe the &s;ervant hur|ried me in on your approach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you didn't come to meet Lady Waitfort?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I come to meet Lady Waitfort!&mdash;no, I came to read my Epilogue to Neville, and a wonderful production it is&mdash;I'll read it to you&mdash;"The tyrant totters, and the &s;enate nods"</P>
<STAGE><HI>(walking about with great confidence.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>To what a &s;trange fatality of circum&s;tances has her character been expo&s;ed! but vice often finds its pu|ni&s;hment for a crime never committed, when it e&s;capes for thou&s;ands it daily practi&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Mi&s;s Courtney, I hope your apprehen&s;ions are all at an end.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="48" REF="46">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir; I &s;hall remain for the &s;hort time ne|ce&s;&s;ary to prepare for my journey&mdash;and beg I may detain you no longer&mdash;I'm afraid I have already been a great intruder.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;you have been the occa&s;ion of more hap|pine&s;s than ever I experienc'd, but you won't leave Bath till you have &s;een my brother.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I have been cruelly deceived Mr Flori|velle, I have injured your brother &s;o much, that tho' I wi&s;h, I almo&s;t dread to &s;ee him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I'll go in &s;earch of him, and if I don't reconcile you&mdash;come Mr Vapid, will you walk?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR. (<HI>Taking</HI> Vapid <HI>by the hand.</HI>)</SPEAKER>
<P>By heaven an ho|ne&s;t fellow, and if all poets were like you, I'd become one my&s;elf&mdash;Mi&s;s Courtney adieu, expect me to return.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, good night, if I can be of any &s;ervice in the dramatic, or any other way, you may command me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I'll an&s;wer for him, he would die to &s;erve you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Die to &s;erve her!&mdash;ay&mdash;die all! die nobly! die like demi Gods.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE&mdash;<HI>An apartment at Lady</HI> WAITFORT'S.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> WAITFORT <HI>and</HI> LETTY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady WAITFORT.</SPEAKER>
<P>MR Vapid not come yet Letty?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>No madam&mdash;but the &s;ervant who found him at the tavern, &s;aid he would be here immediately.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I prote&s;t I'm almo&s;t weary of them all&mdash; See who's there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LETTY.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr Vapid at la&s;t, now pray your lady&s;hip, in|&s;i&s;t on his explaining every thing to my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; but vilely as he has treated me, I mu&s;t &s;till be calm.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="49" REF="47">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Walk in &s;ir, walk in.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>No ma'am&mdash;I'd rather &s;tay here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg you'll walk in Mr Vapid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>Enters gently.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash; Pray be &s;eated &s;ir, I have &s;omething of con&s;equence to impart to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'd never have ventured, but in hopes of &s;eeing my dear Marianne.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, I will not detain you a moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well ma'am, if that's the ca&s;e, <STAGE><HI>&s;lowly &s;eating him&s;elf</HI></STAGE> its very alarming!</P>
<STAGE><HI>A&s;ide.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Letty, leave the room and fa&s;ten the door.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, <STAGE><HI>turning to</HI> Letty,</STAGE> don't fa&s;ten the door, I be&s;eech you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're very much frightened, Mr Vapid! I hope you don't think I've any de&s;igns again&s;t you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know really ma'am, &s;uch things are per|fectly dramatic</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but I relea&s;e you from your fears, I'll tell you why I have given you this trouble&mdash;my bu|&s;ine&s;s, Mr Vapid, was to conver&s;e with you on the farci|cal affair that happen'd at Neville's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farcical!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, the farcical affair that happen'd at Mr Neville's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farcical! what my Epilogue, ma'am! I hope you don't mean to reflect on that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir, far from it&mdash;I have no doubt but it is a very elegant compo&s;ition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doubt! here it is&mdash;read it&mdash;the very fir&s;t pro|duction of the age&mdash;a regular climax of poetic beauty &mdash;the la&s;t line the <HI>ne plus ultra</HI> of genius.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>But to be &s;erious, Mr Vapid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I <HI>am</HI> &s;erious&mdash;and I'll tell you Lady Wait|fort &mdash;'Tis the la&s;t line of an Epilogue, and the la&s;t &s;cene of a comedy that always di&s;tracts me&mdash;'tis the reconcilia|tion of lovers&mdash;there's the difficulty!&mdash;you find it &s;o in real life I dare &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but Mr Vapid, this affair concerns me exceedingly, and I wi&s;h to know what is to be done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you&mdash;write a play, and bad as it may po&s;|&s;ibly be, and I dare &s;ay 'twill be bad enough, yet &s;ay 'tis a tran&s;lation from the French, and interweave a few
<PB N="50" REF="48">compliments on the Engli&s;h, and my life on't it does wonders&mdash;do it, and &s;ay you had the thought from me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, do you mean to in&s;ult me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>But only be cautious in your &s;tyle,&mdash;women are in general apt to indulge that warm luxuriancy of fancy they po&s;&s;e&s;s&mdash;but do be careful&mdash;be decent&mdash;if you are not, I've done with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I de&s;ire you'll be more re&s;pectful&mdash;I don't under&s;tand it at all</P>
<STAGE><HI>(ri&s;ing.)</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then here comes one that will explain every thing.</P>
<LG>
<L>"There's in her all that we believe of Heav'n,</L>
<L>Amazing brightne&s;s, purity and truth,</L>
<L>Eternal joy and everla&s;ting love."</L>
</LG>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MARIANNE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Marianne, my &s;weet little partner, I rejoice to &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>And my dear &s;weet Mr Poet, I rejoice to &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Provoking! hav'n't I told you a thou&s;and times not to break in upon me when I am alone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alone! My lady, do you reckon Mr Vapid no|body them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Suppo&s;e I &s;hou'd, what is it to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I have no notion of your nobodies&mdash;I al|ways thought them harmle&s;s unmeaning things&mdash;but Mr Vapid's not &s;o very harmle&s;s either&mdash;are you Mr Vapid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed ma'am, I am not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>There now I told you &s;o&mdash;upon my word you rely too much on your time of life&mdash;you do indeed&mdash;you think becau&s;e you're a little the wor&s;e for wear, you may tru&s;t your&s;elf any where&mdash;but you're mi&s;taken&mdash;you're not near &s;o bad as you imagine&mdash;nay, nay I don't flatter, do I Mr Vapid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed ma'am you do not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye Mi&s;s&mdash;your in&s;olence is not to be borne&mdash;you have been the chief cau&s;e of all my perplexity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay aunt, don't &s;ay that.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter, your behaviour is &s;hameful, and it is high time I exert the authority of a relation&mdash;you are a di&s;grace to me&mdash;to your&s;elf and your friends&mdash; therefore I'm determin'd to put into execution a &s;cheme I have long thought of.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="51" REF="49">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it? &s;omething plea&s;ing I hope.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but you &s;hall retire to a convent, till you take po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of your fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>A convent! Oh Lord! I can't make up my mind to it, now don't, pray don't think of it&mdash;I declare its quite &s;hocking.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is a far better place than you de&s;erve&mdash; my re&s;olution is fix'd, and we &s;hall &s;ee whether a life of &s;olitude and au&s;terity, will not awaken &s;ome &s;en&s;e of &s;hame in you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I can't bear the thoughts of it&mdash;Oh do &s;peak to her Mr Vapid, tell her about the na&s;ty monks, now do&mdash;A convent! mercy! what a check to the pa&s;&s;ions? Oh! I can't bear it.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Weeping.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Gad here's a &s;udden touch of tragedy&mdash;pray Lady Waitfort, reflect, you can't &s;end a lady to a con|vent while the theatres are open&mdash;&s;ee it will break the poor girl's heart&mdash;Don't weep &s;o Marianne.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't help it&mdash;it will be the death of me&mdash; pray my dear aunt&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not a word&mdash;I'm determin'd&mdash;to morrow you &s;hall leave this country, and then I have done with you for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, my poor heart!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>See, &s;he'll faint!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, oh!</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>faints in Lady</HI> Waitfort<HI>'s arms.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I have gone too far, what's to be done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some relief immediately, or &s;he'll expire&mdash; where &s;hall I fly, I'll call the &s;ervants.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, 'twill be too late&mdash;I have &s;ome drops in the next clo&s;et may recover her&mdash;hold her a moment, and for heaven's &s;ake take care of her.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>(Marianne <HI>lies in</HI> Vapid<HI>'s arms.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor girl! how I pity her! I really loved her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you really love me, Mr Vapid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hey day recovered! here's incident!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>But did you really love me, Mr Vapid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I did&mdash;what &s;tage effect!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>And wou'd you have really run away with me Mr Vapid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I really wou'd&mdash;a new &s;ituation!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="52" REF="50">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then come along this moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! here's the old lady! keep dying as be|fore, and we'll effect the bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;more equivoque!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Re-enter Lady</HI> Waitfort.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. Wait.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Mr Vapid, how does &s;he do now? Lord! She's in &s;trong convul&s;ions!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, ma'am, &s;he's dying! where are the drops?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>There are very few&mdash;are there any more of the &s;ame kind?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes &s;ir, plenty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fetch them&mdash;'tis the only hope&mdash;if you have any hartshorn too, bring a little of that&mdash;our feelings will need it all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very true Mr Vapid&mdash;I declare to you I'm quite &s;hock'd!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Mr Vapid&mdash;now let's run away&mdash;come &mdash;why what are you thinking of?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>My la&s;t &s;cene&mdash;and I fear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you fear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>That it can't be managed&mdash;let me &s;ee&mdash;we cer|tainly run away, and &s;he returns&mdash;faith I mu&s;t &s;ee her return.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, pray let us be gone, think of this ano|ther time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>So I will, it will do for the fourth tho' not for the fifth act&mdash;therefore my dear little girl come away, and we'll live and die together!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Die together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, die all! die nobly! die like demi gods!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lady WAITFORT <HI>(with two large &s;melling bottles.)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. WAIT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here Mr Vapid, here's the drops&mdash;What gone, mercy on me!&mdash;but no matter I wrong my&s;elf to think of her, I'll follow my lord, and if he &s;till avoids me, I'll have done with them all for ever&mdash;ruin'd by a time-killer!&mdash;by a writer of Epilogues!&mdash;Oh! I &s;hall bur&s;t with di&s;appointment.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;An apartment in <HI>Neville's</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>E$ter</HI> LOULA COURTNEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Still in the fame hou&s;e, yet &s;till afraid to meet him&mdash;Oh Neville! my &s;uperior in every thing! how
<PB N="53" REF="51">can I hope for your forgivene&s;s? While you revealed an affection it had done you credit to deny, I concealed a pa&s;&s;ion I might have been proud to confe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> VAPID <HI>and</HI> MARRIANNE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mi&s;s Courtney, my &s;weet Mi&s;s Courtney! Mr Vapid has run away with me, and I'm &s;o frighten'd for fear of Lady Waitfort.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he may well alarm you&mdash;&s;he has de&s;troy'd my peace for ever! but have you &s;een Mr Neville? Yet why do I a&s;k?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Seen Mr Neville! What, doesn't he yet know you are in his lodgings?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, and I hope never will, the moment his bro|ther returns, I &s;hall &s;et out for my uncle's, and perhaps never &s;ee him more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why not &s;ee him Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I cannot bear the fight of one I have &s;o injured</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>This will do, this will do&mdash;mutual equivoque! equal mi&s;under&s;tanding! my own ca&s;e exactly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your own ca&s;e Mr Vapid! Lord you ba&s;e man! have you got a young lady in your longings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ridiculous!&mdash;don't talk about your ladies, at &s;uch an awful time&mdash;the very &s;ituation in my comedy!&mdash; the la&s;t &s;cene to a &s;yllable&mdash;here's an opportunity of im|proving the denouement.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> PETER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma'am, my ma&s;ter is return'd&mdash;the occa&s;ion of his delay has been a long interview with Mr Willough by &mdash;he doesn't know you are here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marianne excu&s;e me, you'll be &s;afe from Lady Waitfort here&mdash;Indeed I'm very ill.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, where are you going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas! any where to avoid him.&mdash;Farewell! and may you enjoy that happine&s;s I have for ever lo&s;t.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor dear girl! I mu&s;tn't leave her thus.&mdash;Mr Vapid, we won't run away till &s;omething is done for her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go&mdash;there's a good girl&mdash;follow and comfort her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will. Lord, if they mu&s;t be happy in being friends again, what mu&s;t I be who make them &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit after</HI> Loui&s;a.</STAGE>
<PB N="54" REF="52">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>The picture before me! all from nature. I mu&s;t heighten his di&s;tre&s;s&mdash;for contra&s;t is every thing. Peter, not a word for your life. <STAGE><HI>Gives him a tap on the cheek.</HI></STAGE> Not one word, you dull dog.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Neville.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vapid, I'm glad to &s;ee you! Any letter from my brother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor me&s;&s;age?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I need doubt no longer&mdash;'tis evident he avoids me. Cruel ungenerous Floriville.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>[Leaning over his chair.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Courtney will ne|ver &s;ee you again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it&mdash;too well I know it&mdash;that and that only makes me determine to leave this country for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP</SPEAKER>
<P>You are unhappy then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Completely &s;o.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;top. <STAGE><HI>[Sits by him.]</HI></STAGE> She was a divinity, Harry!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>An angel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>And thus to lo&s;e her!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>S'death, don't torment me! <STAGE><HI>[ri&s;ing.]</HI></STAGE> my griefs are already beyond bearing!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>It will do&mdash;he's as unhappy as I could wi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can hold no longer, &s;ir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, you damn'd dog! you'll ruin the cata&s;|trophe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't care&mdash;I'll tell him every thing&mdash;&s;ir&mdash; Mr Neville.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>Taking hold of</HI> Peter <HI>and leading him forward.</HI>]</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye, you villain! do you ever go to a play? Do you ever &s;it in the gallery?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>PET.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, &s;ometimes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then know this is all for your good&mdash;you'll ap|plaud this &s;ome day or other, you dog. Cur&s;e it, won't he be happy enough by and by.&mdash;What, you are going abroad, Neville?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, for ever&mdash;Farewell, Vapid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, Neville! Good night. Now for the effect! Mi&s;s Courtney is in the next room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>What!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="55" REF="53">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Courtney is in the next room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Loui&s;a! Is it po&s;&s;ible?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's light and &s;hade.&mdash;Yes, your brother brought her here, and &s;he expects him to return ev'ry moment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brother! Then 'tis he means to marry her&mdash;nay, perhaps they are already married.&mdash;Heavens! I &s;hall go wild!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't go wild&mdash;that will ruin the denouement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter&mdash;I'm re&s;olv'd, I'll bid her farewell for ever. Vapid, 'tis the la&s;t favour I &s;hall a&s;k of you, give her this letter, and tell her, &s;ince I have re&s;ented Willoughby's attack upon her honour, I think I may be allowed to vindicate my own, &s;till great as have been my faults, my truth has &s;till been greater, and wherever I wander&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a flouri&s;h now. Why you misunder&s;tand&mdash;&s;he is not married, nor going to be married.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, this is no time for raillery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Raillery! Why I am &s;erious&mdash;&s;erious as the la&s;t act&mdash;Zounds! go to her, pre&s;erve the unity of the action; marry her directly, and if the cata&s;trophe does not con|clude with &s;pirit, why damn my comedy&mdash;damn my comedy, that's all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Would to heaven you were in earne&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Earne&s;t&mdash;why there it is now&mdash;the women, dear creatures, are alway's ready enough to produce effect; but the men are &s;o cur&s;t undramatic&mdash;Go to her&mdash;I tell you go to her. Here is my lord and your brother with him. Come go to the lady&mdash;make as good an exit as you can. Two flouri&s;hes&mdash;that will do.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Nev.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Lord SCRATCH <HI>and</HI> FLORIVELLE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>That cur&s;t dramatic maniac&mdash;if I &s;ee him again&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear uncle, con&s;ent to Harry's marriage, and depend on't, he &s;hall trouble you no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you again, I will not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you give any hopes of future con&s;ent?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>By the word of a Peer, I will not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma&s;ter Brook, let me per&s;uade you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Flames and firebrands! the fiend again!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="56" REF="54">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give your con&s;ent, and I'll give Neville a for|tune&mdash;he &s;hall have the entire profits of the different plays in which I intend to introduce your&s;elf and the old Lady Hurlothrumbo.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, that I was not a Peer! If I was any thing el&s;e, but thank heaven, Loui&s;a is more aver&s;e to the match than my&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is &s;he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;he knows his fal&s;ehold, and de&s;pi&s;es him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, you are confident of it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out of my way, &s;ir, I'll not an&s;wer you, I'll go take her to town directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, ma&s;ter Brook&mdash;&s;he's in that room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where, behind me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the$e&mdash;there. <STAGE><HI>(pointing.)</HI></STAGE> Now for it&mdash;what an effect! Oh, charming!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Lord</HI> Scratch <HI>$pens the door, and di&s;covers</HI> Neville <HI>kneeling to</HI> Loui&s;a, <HI>and</HI> Marrianne <HI>with them.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, Peter! there's a cata&s;trophe! Shake|&s;pear's invention's nothing to it! applaud it, you dog&mdash;applaud it&mdash;clap, Peter, clap.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>What are you at, you impudent ra&s;cal, get out of the room.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit</HI> Peter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hould &s;et this down, I may forget.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has a very bad memory&mdash;Lord, I hope he won't forget our marriage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Loui&s;a, what am I to think?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I have wrong$d thee Neville.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Harry, let this be my apology for not having &s;een you before <STAGE><HI>(Gives a deed.)</HI></STAGE> Mi&s;s Cour$ney, ten thou&s;and joys; and could I have found my brother, you &s;hould have &s;een him &s;ooner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>NEV.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, here is a deed of gift for half your e&s;tate.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it, but &s;ay nothing; when you gav$ me money, five years ago, did I &s;ay any thing? No, I $orgot it as &s;oon as it was over, and &s;hould never have reccol|lected it at this moment, but for my lord's inhumanity. Uncle, I thank you, you have made me the happie&s;t man alive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't perplex me, what a compound of folly and genero&s;ity.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="57" REF="55">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Uncle-in-law, what are your feelings on this oc|ca&s;ion, as my aunt &s;ays.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Feelings! I never knew a Peer have any.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, but now I find the contrary; I be|gin to think I've a heart like other men&mdash;it's better to a|tone for an error than per&s;i&s;t in one, therefore give me that deed, Neville. There &s;ir, <STAGE>(<HI>giving it back to</HI> Flori|velle)</STAGE> do you think nobody has e&s;tates to give away but your&s;elf&mdash;Loui&s;a and her fortune are your's Mr Neville, and after my death you &s;hall have mine&mdash;and now there's a cur&s;t burden off my mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now you're a dear creature! and I won't mar|ry&mdash;that's what I won't without con&s;ulting you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>You marry! why &s;hou'd you marry, and how came you here pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>A gentleman run away with me, he is now in the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the room! What Florivelle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>No behind you</P>
<STAGE>(<HI>pointing to</HI> Vapid <HI>who is writing at the table.</HI>)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gho&s;t's and &s;pectres! my evil genius!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come my dear, haven't you almo&s;t fini&s;hed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP. <HI>(Ri&s;ing)</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, the denouement is compleat, and now my dear I re&s;ign my&s;elf to love and you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, my good lord, pray give con&s;ent, my hu&s;band will get money tho' I have none.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>None&mdash;I dare &s;ay he can tell you he will have twelve thou&s;and pounds in le&s;s than a year.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I? Then faith Mr Vapid, we'll build a theatre of our own&mdash;you &s;hall write plays and I'll act them.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ENNUI.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've an idea I give you joy Mr Neville&mdash;I mean to kill time by living &s;ingle and therefore I hope the lady and the borough may be yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr Ennui, I hope you'll pardon me and &s;ir Harry Hu&s;tle the fatigue we occa&s;ioned you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't mention it&mdash;yaw, yaw,&mdash;the very recol|lection makes me faint&mdash;in fact my lord, I ju&s;t met one of Lady Waitfort's &s;ervants who tells me &s;he has left Bath in a rage.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="58" REF="56">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm afraid &s;he has e&s;caped too ea&s;ily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, damn her! never think of her&mdash;I can an&s;wer for her puni&s;hment being adequate to her crimes&mdash;Willoughby has told me all her &s;chemes, and if ever I hear her name again; may I lo&s;e my peerage and be forced to dre&s;s like a gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>My lord! I've an idea.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir I beg your pardon; but really if you have an idea, I'll be much obliged to you if you'll &s;pare it me for my comedy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>In fact, I don't comprehend, I have read your <HI>die-all</HI> Epilogue, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh then &s;ir, I don't wonder at your having ideas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ENN.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I &s;hall expect &s;atisfaction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>VAP.</SPEAKER>
<P>Satisfaction! &s;ir, if any one in&s;ults me I'll lick 'em on the &s;tage &s;ir, that's my way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>L. SCRATCH.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, never mind him, the poor fellow is always talking of what he never had&mdash;Ideas in|deed!&mdash;but come my boy Neville, may you be as happy as I am&mdash;I'm the happie&s;t Peer alive, and I&mdash;when I die&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>FLOR.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I'll an&s;wer for his happine&s;s by my own&mdash;Mi&s;s Courtney, notwith&s;tanding my brother, I will &s;till live in your eye, die in your lap&mdash;and be buried in your heart, and moreover I will &s;tay with you both in England, and never return to Italy again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LOU.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes Florivelle.</P>
<LG>
<L>"And thus behold what ev'ry hour &s;hall prove</L>
<L>"That real happine&s;s is&mdash;mutual love.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
<TRAILER>FINIS.</TRAILER>
